initial_story: having the potential for high speed, high throughput, and low energy cost,optical neural networks (onns) have emerged as a promising candidate foraccelerating deep learning tasks. in conventional onns, light amplitudes aremodulated at the input and detected at the output. however, the light phasesare still ignored in conventional structures, although they can also carryinformation for computing. to address this issue, in this paper, we propose aframework called oplixnet to compress the areas of onns by modulating inputimage data into the amplitudes and phase parts of light signals. the input andoutput parts of the onns are redesigned to make full use of both amplitude andphase information. moreover, mutual learning across different onn structures isintroduced to maintain the accuracy. experimental results demonstrate that theproposed framework significantly reduces the areas of onns with the accuracywithin an acceptable range. for instance, 75.03% area is reduced with a 0.33%accuracy decrease on fully connected neural network (fcnn) and 74.88% area isreduced with a 2.38% accuracy decrease on resnet-32.
stories: Inspired by the potential of optical neural networks (ONNs) to accelerate deep learning tasks, researchers have developed a new framework called OplixNet. Unlike conventional ONNs that only modulate light amplitudes, OplixNet leverages both amplitude and phase information of light signals to compress the network areas. By redesigning the input and output parts of ONNs, OplixNet effectively utilizes the phase information for computing, leading to significant area reduction while maintaining acceptable accuracy levels. In experimental results, OplixNet reduced ONN areas by 75.03% with only a 0.33% accuracy decrease in fully connected neural networks (FCNN), and by 74.88% with a 2.38% accuracy decrease in ResNet-32. This breakthrough in ONN architecture shows promise for optimizing deep learning tasks efficiently and effectively.

Drawing inspiration from the success of OplixNet in utilizing both amplitude and phase information for deep learning tasks, a team of researchers has introduced a new concept called PhaseBoostNet. Unlike traditional neural networks that focus solely on amplitude modulation, PhaseBoostNet integrates phase information into the network architecture to enhance performance and reduce computational complexity. By leveraging phase information for computations, PhaseBoostNet demonstrates a remarkable 80.15% reduction in network areas for FCNN models with only a 0.15% decrease in accuracy, and a 79.42% reduction for ResNet-50 models with a 1.92% decrease in accuracy. These results highlight the potential of PhaseBoostNet in streamlining deep learning tasks and optimizing efficiency in neural network design.

Inspired by the groundbreaking advancements in neural network design, a group of innovators have developed a cutting-edge system known as PhaseEnhanceNet. These breakthrough findings underscore the immense potential of PhaseEnhanceNet in revolutionizing the landscape of artificial intelligence and paving the way for more efficient and effective neural network designs.
